Observation Details: After yesterday evening's discovery of 6 new goslings at this pond, I was anxious to come back and check on them. A couple who live on my street walked up shortly after I arrived and we immediately began talking about the goslings. My neighbor said that the mother of this brood was recently struck and killed on the road next to the pond, and after her death, the father flew off and abandoned the babies. He has not returned, so the babies are orphans and are on their own. Luckily, the resident pair of adults are still here with their single gosling (which is older and more developed than the orphans - see photo), but all 3 of them shun the orphans and periodically chase them (see photo). Luckily, the little ones keep coming back and try to stay as close to the adults as the adults will tolerate.

In addition to the four subspecies of CACG, there are currently seven recognized subspecies of CANG, making eleven "taxa" total in this whole taxonomic group. Each of the eleven taxa bear familiar physiological similarities, such as the white cheek against a dark neck sock and brown wings with black flight feathers. But they also represent many continuous phenotypic spectrums, from size to bill shape to vocalization. Today’s difficult ID problems are the inherited woes of yesterday’s troubled taxonomic organization.  All eleven subspecies are endemic to North America; where they are found elsewhere globally they are vagrants or naturalized introduced populations, and often the source of conflict. And throughout their native range, too, they possess a checkered past.   At the turn of the 20th century, habitat loss and overhunting had taken many populations of Canadas to the brink, perhaps none more so than the biggest subspecies, B.c. maxima: the “Giant” goose. When a last remnant breeding population was discovered, the birds were reintroduced to many parts of eastern North America where they began to breed with other local populations and the species once again dominated the wetlands and the plains. Today, most breeding and year-round geese in the east are genetic mutts, a complete mix of the original smaller, migratory subspecies and the larger, less migratory subspecies. These are the birds which terrorize kids at parks, block putts on golf greens, and cost the US millions annually in agricultural loss and vehicle damage. These are your lakefront pests, your cute barnyard goslings, your strip mall grazers, and one of the more polarizing birds in the region's cultural history.  With theory and context out of the way, it’s time to be pragmatic about eastern winter goose ID. To be scientifically exact, these mutts are composed of the genes of four subspecies. The first two are the largest ssp -‘moffs’ and ‘max’- and are essentially indistinguishable in the field. The second two are the two intermediate eastern ssp, which are also virtually unidentifiable. Because of this, eBird splits them into two “slash taxons”: ‘B.c. moffitti/maxima’, and ‘B.c. interior group’ (which includes ssp B.c. interior, canadensis, and parvipes). Now, the way to report these Atlantic breeding birds is not using either of those taxon options but instead simply use the unspecific “Canada Goose”. There is ultimately no way of uncovering most of these “resident” birds’ heritage, and if there was, it would be a conversation about mtDNA and divergence well beyond the citizen scientist’s paygrade and the scope of eBird. However, things change somewhat in the fall. As migratory flocks of canadas begin to converge on the flocks of less migratory resident mutts for the winter, the differences become clear. These migratory birds can be much smaller, with no trace of moff/max influence. Although in the vast majority of cases it will be safer (and always correct) to leave these mixed flocks at the species level, there are instances where a separate flock of clearly smaller, usually darker birds can with great caution be labeled ‘canadensis group’ (see that taxon in this list for more).  This is also true of pure moffitti and maxima, which occasionally show up in the east on arrival from their central breeding grounds (full details under that taxon).  There are two subspecies of CANG which are unrecorded in the east, and can be discarded. This is a slash taxon by virtue of similarity: B.c. occidentalis/fulva. Occidentalis is Latin for western, and these two ssp more or less never leave the Pacific coast.   The highly contentious “Lesser” Canada: B.c. parvipes, is included in eBird in the taxon “Canadensis group”, so there is no real reason to try to sus them apart from B.c. interior or B.c. canadensis, and there is probably no good way to either, at least this far east. In short, Lesser is quite a bit more complicated and should be approached with the utmost of caution. It is presumed a rare visitor to the east from its central and western tundra breeding grounds, and its ID is extremely difficult outside of its native range. It overlaps with the largest cacklers in size and shape, and likely intergrades regularly with other intermediate canada ssp where their ranges coincide. Thus, it should be ignored for all intents and purposes. But if you are accidentally looking at one, you probably won’t think it could be a cackler, it will generally look more like a tiny canada.  An additional pseudo-category of geese which often gets brought up is the concept of “runt” birds. But it’s critical to be precise about what we’re saying. In a 2012 article David Sibley writes,   “...technically [runts] is the wrong term. A runt usually means a young animal, still growing (the smallest of a litter of puppies, for example), that is smaller than its siblings. This is common in birds, caused by poor health or poor nutrition, but if runts survive they can grow to full size indistinguishable from their nest-mates. Unusually small adult birds should be called “dwarfs”. ((A runt Common Tern studied by Coulter (1982) was the smallest in the nest, and seemed unlikely to survive, but eventually grew to normal size and fledged, albeit about ten days later than its nest-mates. On the other hand, continued poor nutrition results in birds that never reach full size and remain smaller than normal, as several studies on Snow and Canada Geese have shown))".   Individuals malnourished in their early stages or otherwise abnormally small birds are a regular occurrence, presumably across all taxa. This is why size alone is never diagnostic outside of the extremes. ID of strange, 'tweener' geese should be based on as many field marks as possible in a process of elimination. A dwarf interior CANG might be smaller than a CACG, but it probably won't also have a broad, indented cheek and stubby bill.   That covers CANG. It can be broken down into 3 simple categories: “year-round, resident mutts”, “smaller migratory winterers”, and “massive paler winterers”. Everything beyond that is speculation, but that shouldn't be read with a negative connotation. Speculation is the foundation of science, and documenting birds that don’t fit the mold is the only way to advance the issue.  Enjoy some mutts:

Media notes: Probably the first photo to depict 3 different subspecies of Canada Goose in Alaska:  moffitti, fulva, and parvipes.
Observation Details: Compared with fulva: larger body, thinner and longer neck, lighter breast and dorsum, and white throat/cheek patch is whiter and different in shape.  Steve Heinl wrote in his "Spring 2016 Southeast Alaska Bird Report":  "A large, pale-breasted Canada Goose at the Mendenhall Wetlands 22 April 2016 was identified as subspecies moffitti/maxima (GBV). The bird was described as being slightly larger than the local, dark-breasted fulva Canada Geese it accompanied. There are two prior local reports of large pale-breasted birds (Pt. Bridget S.P., 19 May 2008, PMS; Mendenhall Wetlands, 30 April 2007, GBV), which breed as close as central interior British Columbia (Campbell et al. 1990). Subspecies maxima and moffitti are similar in size and coloration, the differences being largely clinal from western North America (moffitti) east to the Midwest (maxima), and they intergrade extensively; introductions of both subspecies throughout North America have also confused their distributions—as a result, some authors treat them as one subspecies (moffitti; see Mowbray et al. 2002)."  Note the similarity in the dates of at least three of these four observations!  Probably the first photo to depict 3 different subspecies of Canada Goose in Alaska:  moffitti, fulva, and parvipes.

In addition to the four subspecies of CACG, there are currently seven recognized subspecies of CANG, making eleven "taxa" total in this whole taxonomic group. Each of the eleven taxa bear familiar physiological similarities, such as the white cheek against a dark neck sock and brown wings with black flight feathers. But they also represent many continuous phenotypic spectrums, from size to bill shape to vocalization. Today’s difficult ID problems are the inherited woes of yesterday’s troubled taxonomic organization.  All eleven subspecies are endemic to North America; where they are found elsewhere globally they are vagrants or naturalized introduced populations, and often the source of conflict. And throughout their native range, too, they possess a checkered past.   At the turn of the 20th century, habitat loss and overhunting had taken many populations of Canadas to the brink, perhaps none more so than the biggest subspecies, B.c. maxima: the “Giant” goose. When a last remnant breeding population was discovered, the birds were reintroduced to many parts of eastern North America where they began to breed with other local populations and the species once again dominated the wetlands and the plains. Today, most breeding and year-round geese in the east are genetic mutts, a complete mix of the original smaller, migratory subspecies and the larger, less migratory subspecies. These are the birds which terrorize kids at parks, block putts on golf greens, and cost the US millions annually in agricultural loss and vehicle damage. These are your lakefront pests, your cute barnyard goslings, your strip mall grazers, and one of the more polarizing birds in the region's cultural history.  With theory and context out of the way, it’s time to be pragmatic about eastern winter goose ID. To be scientifically exact, these mutts are composed of the genes of four subspecies. The first two are the largest ssp -‘moffs’ and ‘max’- and are essentially indistinguishable in the field. The second two are the two intermediate eastern ssp, which are also virtually unidentifiable. Because of this, eBird splits them into two “slash taxons”: ‘B.c. moffitti/maxima’, and ‘B.c. interior group’ (which includes ssp B.c. interior, canadensis, and parvipes). Now, the way to report these Atlantic breeding birds is not using either of those taxon options but instead simply use the unspecific “Canada Goose”. There is ultimately no way of uncovering most of these “resident” birds’ heritage, and if there was, it would be a conversation about mtDNA and divergence well beyond the citizen scientist’s paygrade and the scope of eBird. However, things change somewhat in the fall. As migratory flocks of canadas begin to converge on the flocks of less migratory resident mutts for the winter, the differences become clear. These migratory birds can be much smaller, with no trace of moff/max influence. Although in the vast majority of cases it will be safer (and always correct) to leave these mixed flocks at the species level, there are instances where a separate flock of clearly smaller, usually darker birds can with great caution be labeled ‘canadensis group’ (see that taxon in this list for more).  This is also true of pure moffitti and maxima, which occasionally show up in the east on arrival from their central breeding grounds (full details under that taxon).  There are two subspecies of CANG which are unrecorded in the east, and can be discarded. This is a slash taxon by virtue of similarity: B.c. occidentalis/fulva. Occidentalis is Latin for western, and these two ssp more or less never leave the Pacific coast.   The highly contentious “Lesser” Canada: B.c. parvipes, is included in eBird in the taxon “Canadensis group”, so there is no real reason to try to sus them apart from B.c. interior or B.c. canadensis, and there is probably no good way to either, at least this far east. In short, Lesser is quite a bit more complicated and should be approached with the utmost of caution. It is presumed a rare visitor to the east from its central and western tundra breeding grounds, and its ID is extremely difficult outside of its native range. It overlaps with the largest cacklers in size and shape, and likely intergrades regularly with other intermediate canada ssp where their ranges coincide. Thus, it should be ignored for all intents and purposes. But if you are accidentally looking at one, you probably won’t think it could be a cackler, it will generally look more like a tiny canada.  An additional pseudo-category of geese which often gets brought up is the concept of “runt” birds. But it’s critical to be precise about what we’re saying. In a 2012 article David Sibley writes,   “...technically [runts] is the wrong term. A runt usually means a young animal, still growing (the smallest of a litter of puppies, for example), that is smaller than its siblings. This is common in birds, caused by poor health or poor nutrition, but if runts survive they can grow to full size indistinguishable from their nest-mates. Unusually small adult birds should be called “dwarfs”. ((A runt Common Tern studied by Coulter (1982) was the smallest in the nest, and seemed unlikely to survive, but eventually grew to normal size and fledged, albeit about ten days later than its nest-mates. On the other hand, continued poor nutrition results in birds that never reach full size and remain smaller than normal, as several studies on Snow and Canada Geese have shown))".   Individuals malnourished in their early stages or otherwise abnormally small birds are a regular occurrence, presumably across all taxa. This is why size alone is never diagnostic outside of the extremes. ID of strange, 'tweener' geese should be based on as many field marks as possible in a process of elimination. A dwarf interior CANG might be smaller than a CACG, but it probably won't also have a broad, indented cheek and stubby bill.   That covers CANG. It can be broken down into 3 simple categories: “year-round, resident mutts”, “smaller migratory winterers”, and “massive paler winterers”. Everything beyond that is speculation, but that shouldn't be read with a negative connotation. Speculation is the foundation of science, and documenting birds that don’t fit the mold is the only way to advance the issue.  Enjoy some mutts:

Observation Details: After yesterday evening's discovery of 6 new goslings at this pond, I was anxious to come back and check on them. A couple who live on my street walked up shortly after I arrived and we immediately began talking about the goslings. My neighbor said that the mother of this brood was recently struck and killed on the road next to the pond, and after her death, the father flew off and abandoned the babies. He has not returned, so the babies are orphans and are on their own. Luckily, the resident pair of adults are still here with their single gosling (which is older and more developed than the orphans - see photo), but all 3 of them shun the orphans and periodically chase them (see photo). Luckily, the little ones keep coming back and try to stay as close to the adults as the adults will tolerate.

Observation Details: This relatively small Canada Goose was resting near the eastern shore and allowed a very close approach. The bird was by itself, unlike all the honkers that are everywhere in pairs now. There were no other waterfowl around for comparison, but it appeared to be a medium-sized goose -- a bit larger and longer-necked than a typical Cackling Goose but smaller than a typical moffitti/maxima Canada Goose. The bill was rather petite, but long and tapered instead of stubby-looking.  Based on these features, it appears to belong to the candensis group of the Canada Goose. See photos.

In addition to the four subspecies of CACG, there are currently seven recognized subspecies of CANG, making eleven "taxa" total in this whole taxonomic group. Each of the eleven taxa bear familiar physiological similarities, such as the white cheek against a dark neck sock and brown wings with black flight feathers. But they also represent many continuous phenotypic spectrums, from size to bill shape to vocalization. Today’s difficult ID problems are the inherited woes of yesterday’s troubled taxonomic organization.  All eleven subspecies are endemic to North America; where they are found elsewhere globally they are vagrants or naturalized introduced populations, and often the source of conflict. And throughout their native range, too, they possess a checkered past.   At the turn of the 20th century, habitat loss and overhunting had taken many populations of Canadas to the brink, perhaps none more so than the biggest subspecies, B.c. maxima: the “Giant” goose. When a last remnant breeding population was discovered, the birds were reintroduced to many parts of eastern North America where they began to breed with other local populations and the species once again dominated the wetlands and the plains. Today, most breeding and year-round geese in the east are genetic mutts, a complete mix of the original smaller, migratory subspecies and the larger, less migratory subspecies. These are the birds which terrorize kids at parks, block putts on golf greens, and cost the US millions annually in agricultural loss and vehicle damage. These are your lakefront pests, your cute barnyard goslings, your strip mall grazers, and one of the more polarizing birds in the region's cultural history.  With theory and context out of the way, it’s time to be pragmatic about eastern winter goose ID. To be scientifically exact, these mutts are composed of the genes of four subspecies. The first two are the largest ssp -‘moffs’ and ‘max’- and are essentially indistinguishable in the field. The second two are the two intermediate eastern ssp, which are also virtually unidentifiable. Because of this, eBird splits them into two “slash taxons”: ‘B.c. moffitti/maxima’, and ‘B.c. interior group’ (which includes ssp B.c. interior, canadensis, and parvipes). Now, the way to report these Atlantic breeding birds is not using either of those taxon options but instead simply use the unspecific “Canada Goose”. There is ultimately no way of uncovering most of these “resident” birds’ heritage, and if there was, it would be a conversation about mtDNA and divergence well beyond the citizen scientist’s paygrade and the scope of eBird. However, things change somewhat in the fall. As migratory flocks of canadas begin to converge on the flocks of less migratory resident mutts for the winter, the differences become clear. These migratory birds can be much smaller, with no trace of moff/max influence. Although in the vast majority of cases it will be safer (and always correct) to leave these mixed flocks at the species level, there are instances where a separate flock of clearly smaller, usually darker birds can with great caution be labeled ‘canadensis group’ (see that taxon in this list for more).  This is also true of pure moffitti and maxima, which occasionally show up in the east on arrival from their central breeding grounds (full details under that taxon).  There are two subspecies of CANG which are unrecorded in the east, and can be discarded. This is a slash taxon by virtue of similarity: B.c. occidentalis/fulva. Occidentalis is Latin for western, and these two ssp more or less never leave the Pacific coast.   The highly contentious “Lesser” Canada: B.c. parvipes, is included in eBird in the taxon “Canadensis group”, so there is no real reason to try to sus them apart from B.c. interior or B.c. canadensis, and there is probably no good way to either, at least this far east. In short, Lesser is quite a bit more complicated and should be approached with the utmost of caution. It is presumed a rare visitor to the east from its central and western tundra breeding grounds, and its ID is extremely difficult outside of its native range. It overlaps with the largest cacklers in size and shape, and likely intergrades regularly with other intermediate canada ssp where their ranges coincide. Thus, it should be ignored for all intents and purposes. But if you are accidentally looking at one, you probably won’t think it could be a cackler, it will generally look more like a tiny canada.  An additional pseudo-category of geese which often gets brought up is the concept of “runt” birds. But it’s critical to be precise about what we’re saying. In a 2012 article David Sibley writes,   “...technically [runts] is the wrong term. A runt usually means a young animal, still growing (the smallest of a litter of puppies, for example), that is smaller than its siblings. This is common in birds, caused by poor health or poor nutrition, but if runts survive they can grow to full size indistinguishable from their nest-mates. Unusually small adult birds should be called “dwarfs”. ((A runt Common Tern studied by Coulter (1982) was the smallest in the nest, and seemed unlikely to survive, but eventually grew to normal size and fledged, albeit about ten days later than its nest-mates. On the other hand, continued poor nutrition results in birds that never reach full size and remain smaller than normal, as several studies on Snow and Canada Geese have shown))".   Individuals malnourished in their early stages or otherwise abnormally small birds are a regular occurrence, presumably across all taxa. This is why size alone is never diagnostic outside of the extremes. ID of strange, 'tweener' geese should be based on as many field marks as possible in a process of elimination. A dwarf interior CANG might be smaller than a CACG, but it probably won't also have a broad, indented cheek and stubby bill.   That covers CANG. It can be broken down into 3 simple categories: “year-round, resident mutts”, “smaller migratory winterers”, and “massive paler winterers”. Everything beyond that is speculation, but that shouldn't be read with a negative connotation. Speculation is the foundation of science, and documenting birds that don’t fit the mold is the only way to advance the issue.  Enjoy some mutts:

But they also represent many continuous phenotypic spectrums, from size to bill shape to vocalization. Today’s difficult ID problems are the inherited woes of yesterday’s troubled taxonomic organization.  All eleven subspecies are endemic to North America; where they are found elsewhere globally they are vagrants or naturalized introduced populations, and often the source of conflict. And throughout their native range, too, they possess a checkered past.   At the turn of the 20th century, habitat loss and overhunting had taken many populations of Canadas to the brink, perhaps none more so than the biggest subspecies, B.c. maxima: the “Giant” goose. When a last remnant breeding population was discovered, the birds were reintroduced to many parts of eastern North America where they began to breed with other local populations and the species once again dominated the wetlands and the plains. Today, most breeding and year-round geese in the east are genetic mutts, a complete mix of the original smaller, migratory subspecies and the larger, less migratory subspecies. These are the birds which terrorize kids at parks, block putts on golf greens, and cost the US millions annually in agricultural loss and vehicle damage. These are your lakefront pests, your cute barnyard goslings, your strip mall grazers, and one of the more polarizing birds in the region's cultural history.  With theory and context out of the way, it’s time to be pragmatic about eastern winter goose ID. To be scientifically exact, these mutts are composed of the genes of four subspecies. The first two are the largest ssp -‘moffs’ and ‘max’- and are essentially indistinguishable in the field. The second two are the two intermediate eastern ssp, which are also virtually unidentifiable. Because of this, eBird splits them into two “slash taxons”: ‘B.c. moffitti/maxima’, and ‘B.c. interior group’ (which includes ssp B.c. interior, canadensis, and parvipes). Now, the way to report these Atlantic breeding birds is not using either of those taxon options but instead simply use the unspecific “Canada Goose”. There is ultimately no way of uncovering most of these “resident” birds’ heritage, and if there was, it would be a conversation about mtDNA and divergence well beyond the citizen scientist’s paygrade and the scope of eBird. However, things change somewhat in the fall. As migratory flocks of canadas begin to converge on the flocks of less migratory resident mutts for the winter, the differences become clear. These migratory birds can be much smaller, with no trace of moff/max influence. Although in the vast majority of cases it will be safer (and always correct) to leave these mixed flocks at the species level, there are instances where a separate flock of clearly smaller, usually darker birds can with great caution be labeled ‘canadensis group’ (see that taxon in this list for more).  This is also true of pure moffitti and maxima, which occasionally show up in the east on arrival from their central breeding grounds (full details under that taxon).  There are two subspecies of CANG which are unrecorded in the east, and can be discarded. This is a slash taxon by virtue of similarity: B.c. occidentalis/fulva. Occidentalis is Latin for western, and these two ssp more or less never leave the Pacific coast.   The highly contentious “Lesser” Canada: B.c. parvipes, is included in eBird in the taxon “Canadensis group”, so there is no real reason to try to sus them apart from B.c. interior or B.c. canadensis, and there is probably no good way to either, at least this far east. In short, Lesser is quite a bit more complicated and should be approached with the utmost of caution. It is presumed a rare visitor to the east from its central and western tundra breeding grounds, and its ID is extremely difficult outside of its native range. It overlaps with the largest cacklers in size and shape, and likely intergrades regularly with other intermediate canada ssp where their ranges coincide. Thus, it should be ignored for all intents and purposes. But if you are accidentally looking at one, you probably won’t think it could be a cackler, it will generally look more like a tiny canada.  An additional pseudo-category of geese which often gets brought up is the concept of “runt” birds. But it’s critical to be precise about what we’re saying. In a 2012 article David Sibley writes,   “...technically [runts] is the wrong term. A runt usually means a young animal, still growing (the smallest of a litter of puppies, for example), that is smaller than its siblings. This is common in birds, caused by poor health or poor nutrition, but if runts survive they can grow to full size indistinguishable from their nest-mates. Unusually small adult birds should be called “dwarfs”. ((A runt Common Tern studied by Coulter (1982) was the smallest in the nest, and seemed unlikely to survive, but eventually grew to normal size and fledged, albeit about ten days later than its nest-mates. On the other hand, continued poor nutrition results in birds that never reach full size and remain smaller than normal, as several studies on Snow and Canada Geese have shown))".   Individuals malnourished in their early stages or otherwise abnormally small birds are a regular occurrence, presumably across all taxa. This is why size alone is never diagnostic outside of the extremes. ID of strange, 'tweener' geese should be based on as many field marks as possible in a process of elimination. A dwarf interior CANG might be smaller than a CACG, but it probably won't also have a broad, indented cheek and stubby bill.   That covers CANG. It can be broken down into 3 simple categories: “year-round, resident mutts”, “smaller migratory winterers”, and “massive paler winterers”. Everything beyond that is speculation, but that shouldn't be read with a negative connotation. Speculation is the foundation of science, and documenting birds that don’t fit the mold is the only way to advance the issue.  Enjoy some mutts:

Many wintering flocks in the northeast are composed of the two northern central breeding ssp: the nominate B.c. canadensis and B.c. interior. This "canadensis group" taxon in eBird somewhat pragmatically includes B.c. parvipes, making this taxon a 'bucket' in which to toss the smaller migrant birds. This is much more easily done where there are not year-round populations of intermediate genetic mutts, which can merge into wintering flocks of interior birds and confuse the whole situation.   This is where one must ask the question of accuracy vs precision. It is more precise to try to pick out every last bird and put it into a subspecies. However, with a massive range of variation across these types, it is more accurate to simply leave mixed flocks at the species level. In Mass, I use this taxon only when I can identify clearly defined subflocks, particularly family groups, who are smaller/daintier, often slightly darker when compared to paler residents, and associating like migrants (more active, in water more than land), etc. The latter can be subjective, but these impressions will be fairly accurate after spending lots of time watching the flocks. (It may be more difficult, of course, at contained locations such as this pond where birds are often long-staying.)  This family group of 4 includes two hatch years and presumably the adult pair. Their calls were on the higher end of pitch for CANG, and they were substantially smaller, with smaller heads and necks.

The primary field marks for these birds are size, head shape, and coloration. These are big ducks, as big as the chunkiest residents. They generally have a sloping forehead and bill, like a massive Canvasback. They are paler overall, often with a very white breast which can culminate in a white neck ring. Lastly, they have a very broad white cheek, sometimes indented under the eye (a more common trait in cacklers than other canada types), which wraps completely under the chin (no black gular stripe). Sometimes they will have white supraloral spots or even a full white forehead. But most importantly none of these field marks is conclusive alone, nor really any two or three. You want at least four or five of those traits to report a bird under the slash taxa B.c. moffitti/maxima, and at such a point, you certainly should do so.   The two birds in these photos show a lovely variety of those features (virtually all of them). The extent of the white cheek will probably be the thing which catches one's eye first.

The bird calls once at the beginning and once at the end (at the 1 second and 6 second marks).

Majestic Canada Goose. As majestic they are, considering the miles they fly, they are also tough birds. They fly in V formation so that the leader breaks the wind. They take turns leading to give each other rest. If one bird cannot keep up and must land, one other bird goes down with him/her. They pick up with the next set of birds flying over head. If one of the birds is sick, the other stays until it gives up life, and then picks up with another group. Isn't that amazing? What does that tell us? We have the obligation to take care of the most vulnerable!. Elevation: 60 m. Date added to IBC: June 21, 2016.

Canada Geese mates. In the summer, Canada Geese are all over the place in Ottawa, especially near water and marshes. When development is planned, they must consider leaving parkland and water for these birds to land and have babies when they migrate from the north in spring. Elevation: 60 m. Media notes: Duskier chinned and thicker necked of two Lesser-type birds
Observation Details: Including two Lesser-type birds that I won't try to report as a specific subspecies. Two birds were immediately obvious within the flock as smaller, grayer, and shorter-billed. Not small enough and without stubby enough bills to be Cackling. They were even easier to pick out as outsiders once we approached and they separated themselves out from the main group (though acting like a family group/pair by staying together) as slightly more skittish, staying in the back further away from us. One bird had a reduced and duskier white chin strap and showed a thicker neck while the other had a more typical chin strap and thinner neck. Besides these differences there seemed to be no obvious difference in body side between the two. Photos showing size comparison with regular Canada-types and Brant below.

Observation Details: In addition to the four subspecies of CACG, there are currently seven recognized subspecies of CANG, making eleven "taxa" total in this whole taxonomic group. Each of the eleven taxa bear familiar physiological similarities, such as the white cheek against a dark neck sock and brown wings with black flight feathers. But they also represent many continuous phenotypic spectrums, from size to bill shape to vocalization. Today’s difficult ID problems are the inherited woes of yesterday’s troubled taxonomic organization.  All eleven subspecies are endemic to North America; where they are found elsewhere globally they are vagrants or naturalized introduced populations, and often the source of conflict. And throughout their native range, too, they possess a checkered past.   At the turn of the 20th century, habitat loss and overhunting had taken many populations of Canadas to the brink, perhaps none more so than the biggest subspecies, B.c. maxima: the “Giant” goose. When a last remnant breeding population was discovered, the birds were reintroduced to many parts of eastern North America where they began to breed with other local populations and the species once again dominated the wetlands and the plains. Today, most breeding and year-round geese in the east are genetic mutts, a complete mix of the original smaller, migratory subspecies and the larger, less migratory subspecies. These are the birds which terrorize kids at parks, block putts on golf greens, and cost the US millions annually in agricultural loss and vehicle damage. These are your lakefront pests, your cute barnyard goslings, your strip mall grazers, and one of the more polarizing birds in the region's cultural history.  With theory and context out of the way, it’s time to be pragmatic about eastern winter goose ID. To be scientifically exact, these mutts are composed of the genes of four subspecies. The first two are the largest ssp -‘moffs’ and ‘max’- and are essentially indistinguishable in the field. The second two are the two intermediate eastern ssp, which are also virtually unidentifiable. Because of this, eBird splits them into two “slash taxons”: ‘B.c. moffitti/maxima’, and ‘B.c. interior group’ (which includes ssp B.c. interior, canadensis, and parvipes). Now, the way to report these Atlantic breeding birds is not using either of those taxon options but instead simply use the unspecific “Canada Goose”. There is ultimately no way of uncovering most of these “resident” birds’ heritage, and if there was, it would be a conversation about mtDNA and divergence well beyond the citizen scientist’s paygrade and the scope of eBird. However, things change somewhat in the fall. As migratory flocks of canadas begin to converge on the flocks of less migratory resident mutts for the winter, the differences become clear. These migratory birds can be much smaller, with no trace of moff/max influence. Although in the vast majority of cases it will be safer (and always correct) to leave these mixed flocks at the species level, there are instances where a separate flock of clearly smaller, usually darker birds can with great caution be labeled ‘canadensis group’ (see that taxon in this list for more).  This is also true of pure moffitti and maxima, which occasionally show up in the east on arrival from their central breeding grounds (full details under that taxon).  There are two subspecies of CANG which are unrecorded in the east, and can be discarded. This is a slash taxon by virtue of similarity: B.c. occidentalis/fulva. Occidentalis is Latin for western, and these two ssp more or less never leave the Pacific coast.   The highly contentious “Lesser” Canada: B.c. parvipes, is included in eBird in the taxon “Canadensis group”, so there is no real reason to try to sus them apart from B.c. interior or B.c. canadensis, and there is probably no good way to either, at least this far east. In short, Lesser is quite a bit more complicated and should be approached with the utmost of caution. It is presumed a rare visitor to the east from its central and western tundra breeding grounds, and its ID is extremely difficult outside of its native range. It overlaps with the largest cacklers in size and shape, and likely intergrades regularly with other intermediate canada ssp where their ranges coincide. Thus, it should be ignored for all intents and purposes. But if you are accidentally looking at one, you probably won’t think it could be a cackler, it will generally look more like a tiny canada.  An additional pseudo-category of geese which often gets brought up is the concept of “runt” birds. But it’s critical to be precise about what we’re saying. In a 2012 article David Sibley writes,   “...technically [runts] is the wrong term. A runt usually means a young animal, still growing (the smallest of a litter of puppies, for example), that is smaller than its siblings. This is common in birds, caused by poor health or poor nutrition, but if runts survive they can grow to full size indistinguishable from their nest-mates. Unusually small adult birds should be called “dwarfs”. ((A runt Common Tern studied by Coulter (1982) was the smallest in the nest, and seemed unlikely to survive, but eventually grew to normal size and fledged, albeit about ten days later than its nest-mates. On the other hand, continued poor nutrition results in birds that never reach full size and remain smaller than normal, as several studies on Snow and Canada Geese have shown))".   Individuals malnourished in their early stages or otherwise abnormally small birds are a regular occurrence, presumably across all taxa. This is why size alone is never diagnostic outside of the extremes. ID of strange, 'tweener' geese should be based on as many field marks as possible in a process of elimination. A dwarf interior CANG might be smaller than a CACG, but it probably won't also have a broad, indented cheek and stubby bill.   That covers CANG. It can be broken down into 3 simple categories: “year-round, resident mutts”, “smaller migratory winterers”, and “massive paler winterers”. Everything beyond that is speculation, but that shouldn't be read with a negative connotation. Speculation is the foundation of science, and documenting birds that don’t fit the mold is the only way to advance the issue.  Enjoy some mutts:

Observation Details: exact count in the pond and surrounding grasses, including a group of around 10 foraging on the grass slope at NE pond, first saw their heads as I went down to north pond. the pond was completely frozen in the morning but the layer of ice is very thin, probaby less than 1cm, and so I saw many interesting sights: one goose was in a small section of water where the ice was brozen, and it was plowing through the ice like an icebreaker ship trying to reach the bank of pond, leaving a trail of water behind it in the ice. a bunch of other goose probably used the same method and made a small pool of unfrozen water just a bit north of central eastern pond, and they just stayed in the water over there, didn't see them foraging. the pipe outlet at north of pond was spewing water, but most of the ice was still there, with only a small bit of exposed water for the water from the pipe to flow into. several other goose also at west bank just a bit south of central pond, where they also made some holes in the ice and were just staying there. one very cool thing i observed in that group, as I walked south along west bank: when I came close to them as I walked along the bank, they would fly up and attempt to move to a further section of the pond, and land onto the ice; they would then stay on the ice for 2-3 seconds while closing their wings and once their wings was closed their entire weight is put on the ice, so the ice breaks and they splash into the water, dispering the ice - just shows how thin the ice was. saw 2-3 different birds do this, very interesting! later when returning along east pond slope, saw that all the goose were gone from the pond but some were still foraging around the slope at NE pond.  also noted something interesting, seems like some of these goose were the smaller subspecies that I've seen previously at core creek, and there are also some that had a thinner white stripe on face and a different facial pattern, not sure why that is

Observation Details: The primary field marks for these birds are size, head shape, and coloration. These are big ducks, as big as the chunkiest residents. They generally have a sloping forehead and bill, like a massive Canvasback. They are paler overall, often with a very white breast which can culminate in a white neck ring. Lastly, they have a very broad white cheek, sometimes indented under the eye (a more common trait in cacklers than other canada types), which wraps completely under the chin (no black gular stripe). Sometimes they will have white supraloral spots or even a full white forehead. But most importantly none of these field marks is conclusive alone, nor really any two or three. You want at least four or five of those traits to report a bird under the slash taxa B.c. moffitti/maxima, and at such a point, you certainly should do so.   The two birds in these photos show a lovely variety of those features (virtually all of them). The extent of the white cheek will probably be the thing which catches one's eye first.

Observation Details: At least four very dark-colored birds mixed in with a flock of more normal-looking Canadas. Possibly saw a fifth. Seemed smaller and shorter-necked than the others, but not by very much. Much larger than similarly plumaged Cackling Goose subspecies. Not as stubby-billed as Cackling. Noticed some brownish coloring on the birds' chin straps. Didn't even know this upon visiting, but these birds have been documented here by other birders! I was just confused because I was wondering how I was seeing what appeared to be "Dusky" Canada Geese so far away from where they usually winter. Upon reviewing photos, it's apparent that the birds I photographed were some of the same ones documented by others. My first ID of the "Dusky" subspecies.

At least 10 carcass  2 or 3 goofy  Maybe 6 sickies  30 Count inside res does not include the carcasses ...perhaps 50- 80 more in fields  1st photo bird was dead next day ... see following day list...dead beside rock islet It wasn't acting goofy ... but green slime on breast shows wasnt preening properly, and was generally lethargic. Other clues are how are the "left behind " birds acting when the rest of flock go out for evening feed... Usually single birds that are behind  degress and eventually die. Pairs and groups that are active ...are ok.. "Goofy" birds seem to have some or all of the foillowing - balance issues,causing circular swimming  or inability to keep head up straight,distress marked by vocalizations, general lethargy and or erratic behaviour. One flew around and landed very near me ,edge of blackberries in the tall grass rim of reservoir the other day ,which would never happen with healthy bird.   SO far this year i would estimate 13  to 15 dead...compared to a more typical year of about 3... some years only 1 other years up to 5 ....but this is unusual in my experience
